metadata.title: Beechcraft Bonanza
aws::graph::propositions: # Beechcraft Bonanza Model 35 Variants
Model 35 Bonanza was the initial production version with 165 hp (123 kW) Continental E-185 or E-185-1 engine.
Model 35 Bonanza was produced from 1947 to 1948.
Five prototypes of Model 35 Bonanza were built.
1,500 production aircraft of Model 35 Bonanza were built.
A35 Bonanza was produced in 1949.
A35 Bonanza was a Model 35 with higher takeoff weight.
A35 Bonanza featured tubular wing spars.
A35 Bonanza featured nosewheel steering.
701 A35 Bonanza aircraft were built.
B35 Bonanza was produced in 1950.
B35 Bonanza was an A35 with a Continental E-185-8 engine.
480 B35 Bonanza aircraft were built.
C35 Bonanza was produced from 1950 to 1952.
C35 Bonanza was a B35 with a 185hp Continental E-185-11 engine.
C35 Bonanza featured a metal propeller.
C35 Bonanza had larger tail surfaces compared to previous models.
C35 Bonanza had higher takeoff weight compared to previous models.
C35 Bonanza was approved for the Lycoming GO-435-D1 engine.
719 C35 Bonanza aircraft were built.
35R Bonanza was produced in 1951.
35R Bonanza was a remanufactured Model 35 with many improvements introduced on the B35 and C35.
35R Bonanza was meant as an alternative to new C35 production.
C35 Bonanza production suffered from delays due to the Korean War.

text:
### Model 35 Bonanza

35
(19471948), initial production version with 165 hp (123 kW) Continental E-185 or E-185-1 engine, five prototypes and 1,500 production aircraft built.
A35
(1949) Model 35 with higher takeoff weight, tubular wing spars and nosewheel steering, 701 built.
B35
(1950) A35 with a Continental E-185-8 engine, 480 built.
C35
(1950-1952) B35 with a 185hp Continental E-185-11 engine, metal propeller, larger tail surfaces, and higher takeoff weight, approved for the Lycoming GO-435-D1 engine, 719 built.
35R
(1951) Remanufactured Model 35 with many of the improvements introduced on the B35 and C35, meant as an alternative to new C35 production as the latter suffered from delays due to the Korean War.
